sorry <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uaztech.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AzTech</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://omu.kuiki.net/az.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>OMU Faculty</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/30/01 2:16:22 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://omu.kuiki.net/aztech.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Inking with G-pen ?</span><hr size=1> A G-pen is just a type of nib pen...Japanese in fact.  they are used quite extensively by many manga artists.  You basically have a nib holder, and can insert different nibs into it.  Some people call these dip pens, because you have to dip them into a bottle of ink to reload the pen.<br>
<br>
Other names:  Spoon pen, Turnip pen (no, I'm not making these up), Hunt quills, round pens, and Speedballs.  My personal faves are C-5 and C-6 nibs for outlining, as they allow for a lot of variance of line width, based on how much pressure you put on the pen while inking.  For detail work I use 102 and 107 Hunt quills, as the lines can be made very fine due to the fact that they are very sharp.<br>
<br>
Shop around.  Art stores and stationary stores caryy a lot of different types of nibs and holders.<br>
<br>
